## API / Route Handler conventions (Next)

- Route Handlers live under `app/api/.../route.js` (or `.ts`).
- Prefer consistent JSON responses and appropriate HTTP status codes for public APIs.
- Do not expose stack traces, internal paths, or secrets in responses or logs.
- Use environment variables for secrets; never commit real credentials.

*(When a separate Go API exists in-repo, follow versioned paths such as `/v1/...` and shared JSON envelopes as documented for that service.)*

---

## Naming Conventions

| Layer | JavaScript / TypeScript |
|---|---|
| React component | `PascalCase` |
| Functions / hooks | `camelCase` (`useThing`) |
| Route segments | kebab-case folders as needed |
| Types / interfaces | `PascalCase` |

---

## Boundaries — What Must Never Cross

- Prefer **Server Components** by default; use **`"use client"`** only when hooks, browser APIs, or event handlers require it.
- Keep Route Handler logic in `app/api/**` — validate input, set timeouts where appropriate, avoid blocking the event loop unnecessarily for heavy work (consider streaming or background patterns when the product requires it).
- Do not embed secrets in client bundles — server-only env vars for handlers and server components.
- For TypeScript, avoid `any`; define response shapes for fetch/API boundaries.

---

## Environment & Config

- Use `.env.local` / `.env` patterns supported by Next.js; document non-secret variables in `.env.example` when the project uses one.
- No hardcoded API keys or production URLs in source.

---

## Error Handling Philosophy

**Next / React:** Surface errors meaningfully (error boundaries, UI states); avoid silent failures on user-facing flows.

---

## When in Doubt

- Prefer explicit over implicit
- Prefer boring over clever
- New cross-cutting patterns can be proposed as an ADR in `/docs/adr/` when the project adopts that practice
